# Case Study: Phishing Attack

Phishing is one of the most common forms of cybercrime in which attackers try to steal sensitive information such as passwords, banking details, OTPs, or personal data by pretending to be a trusted person or organization.
These scams are usually carried out through fake emails, text messages, websites, or social media messages.

A common phishing incident begins when a student receives a message that appears to be from a bank, college portal, online shopping site, or delivery service
. The message often creates urgency by saying that the account will be blocked, a payment has failed, or some important verification is required.
It then asks the user to click on a link and log in or enter personal details.

Once the victim clicks the fake link, they are taken to a website that looks genuine but is actually controlled by the attacker
. If the user enters login credentials, card details, or OTPs, that information can be stolen immediately. In some cases, the attacker may also gain access to email or payment accounts.

Students are often targeted because they frequently use email, online banking, UPI apps, shopping apps, and educational portals.
The consequences of phishing can include account hacking, financial loss, identity theft, and misuse of personal information.

This case study shows that phishing attacks often succeed not because of technology alone, but because users are tricked into trusting fake messages.
Awareness and careful verification are the best defenses.
